# Interpolation, Extrapolation & LLMs

**Author: Adit Rada**  
**Date: Sep 10, 2024**  

**tl;dr**: To generate truly novel knowledge, models should extrapolate, and for that we need to do RL & search.

## Neural Networks as Function Approximators

There is an obvious appeal of comparing neural networks to neuroscience and the human brain. However, it is best to think of neural networks as function approximation machines that are designed to achieve statistical generalization, occasionally drawing some insights from what we know about the brain, rather than as models of brain function. \[[1](https://www.deeplearningbook.org/)\]

Specifically, neural networks are learning a nonlinear function in very high dimensional space. Unfortunately, our limited human brain can not visualize more than three dimensions, so we can not see and understand what that function looks like. There has been work done by Ian Goodfellow \[[1](https://www.deeplearningbook.org/)\], to project the high-dimensional cost function optimized during training down to 3D:  
![][image1]

At the end of training, a continuous function is learned. Once we have the final function, we can give as input a new x instance, and we get as output f(x).

## Interpolation

Some argue that generative models just regurgitate their training data, and that they don’t generate anything that is not already in the training data. Whereas another camp argues that generative models do generate truly novel things that humans have not generated before. For example, LLMs can [write](https://g.co/gemini/share/a021fb53be90) a poem about “astronauts swimming in volcanoes with dinosaurs”. As another example, diffusion models can generate images of “monkeys fighting fire with bananas”:  
![][image2]

Currently, I stand somewhere in between these two camps. I agree with the former group that generative models are regurgitating the training data, and I also agree with the latter group that generative models are generating novel things like the examples above.

How can these two groups be right at the same time? The answer lies in *interpolation*. Yes, humans *have not* generated pictures of monkeys fighting fire with bananas, but that does not mean we *can not*. I hypothesize that generative models can only do this because they are interpolating on the learned function, that is moving to different points on the function.

For simplicity, let’s assume that each dimension in the high-dimensional space represents a concept \[[2](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9-Jl0dxWQs8&ab_channel=3Blue1Brown), [3](https://www.alignmentforum.org/posts/iGuwZTHWb6DFY3sKB/fact-finding-attempting-to-reverse-engineer-factual-recall)\] (this is over-simplifying things to get the message across). In our toy example, there is one dimension for “monkeys”, there is one dimension for “fire”, and one dimension for “bananas”. These dimensions are “learned” as each of the three concepts appear in the training data *independent of each other*. After training, when the nonlinear and continuous function has been learned, one can move to a point that is in the middle of these three dimensions (by interpolating) even though none of the three dimensions appeared *together* in the training data. And this is why the models can generate images of “monkeys fighting fire with bananas”.

With this view, both groups are right. 1\) Generative models only stick to what is in the training data. 2\) Generative models generate novel things by interpolating between regions from the training data.

## Extrapolation

According to Wikipedia, *extrapolation* is the extension of a graph, curve, or range of values by inferring unknown values from trends in the known data. To generate truly novel knowledge, and new “concepts”, one may need to extrapolate. I hypothesize that generative models do not extrapolate. Hallucination may be an artifact of failed attempts at extrapolation.

A good example of a successful extrapolation is the famous “move 37” made by AlphaGo against Lee Sedol \[[4](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/AlphaGo_versus_Lee_Sedol)\], it was a move that no human would've ever made. This was true “creativity”. Such a move would not have been made by AlphaGo if it was just interpolating, as it would have only stayed on the function surface learned during training. The extrapolation happened due to Monte Carlo Tree Search (MCTS) which allowed AlphaGo to move past the learned region and generate something truly novel.

From my knowledge, the only successful attempts of extrapolation happen when RL and search are employed \[[5](https://www.nature.com/articles/nature16961'), [6](http://www.incompleteideas.net/IncIdeas/BitterLesson.html?ref=blog.heim.xyz)\]. So, on the path to AGI and achieving superintelligence, we would definitely want a system that can generate novel knowledge. To do that, we need to combine AlphaGo like RL and search mechanisms with LLMs. Sparks of this being a promising approach is evidenced by the success of AlphaProof \[[7](https://deepmind.google/discover/blog/ai-solves-imo-problems-at-silver-medal-level/)\], which combines Gemini and AlphaZero’s approach for mathematics.

However, porting this over to general LLMs is challenging because:

* **Continuous state space:** The game of Go is finite and discrete, with transition from one game state to another being clearly defined with no ambiguities. However, the same can not be said of the real world, which is much more messy, and has no clear boundaries between “game states”.  
* **Reward**: The game of Go (where you either win or lose) has a clear reward signal allowing for RL to work its miracles. However, the real world has no clear and unambiguous reward signal. The reward signal may be complex and there may be more than one reward signal \[[8](https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0004370221000862)\]. Finding the reward function for life (if at all possible) will lead us down the philosophical rabbit hole of trying to define the meaning of life.

## Conclusion

Current generation generative models can only interpolate. To generate new knowledge, models will need to extrapolate beyond the learned function. Successfully extrapolating will mean trying to add RL and search on top of the models. Adding RL and search to the models is complicated by the fact that we don’t have good definitions for state and reward in the real world.

Just because it is hard to design the reward function for life, and as an extension for completely general agents, it does not mean that we should give up on this approach. We can start small and target narrow domains \- like drug discovery \- and gradually increase the generality (this is analogous to reward shaping when training RL agents\!).
